Introduction¶

Overview¶

In this project I will be going through the entire data analysis process which include, Asking Questions, Wrangle, Explore(EDA), Draw Conclusion and Communicate critical findings

The analysis process always starts with asking questions. In this project, I have been given a data set so I will glance through the data and pose some relevant questions.

To complete this Data Analysis project I will be using the NoShowAppointments dataset.

Questions:¶

  1. What is the overall appointment show-up vs. no show-up rate?
  2. Does alcoholism affect patient's show up?
  3. Does patients with diabetes show up more than the ones without diabetes?
  4. Does people who have scholarship show up more?
  5. What is the proportions of sms received?
  6. Does sms received affect appointment show rate?
  7. Which location has the most appointment show rate?

Dataset: This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. It can be downloaded from here.

Data Dictionary¶

01 PatientId Identification of a patient

02 - AppointmentID

Identification of each appointment

03 - Gender Male or Female

04 - ScheduledDay The day someone called or registered the appointment, this is before appointment of course.

05 - AppointmentDay The day of the actuall appointment, when they have to visit the doctor.

06 - Age How old is the patient.

07 - Neighbourhood Where the appointment takes place.

08 - Scholarship True of False . Observation, this is a broad topic, consider reading this article here

09 - Hipertension True or False

10 - Diabetes True or False

11 - Alcoholism True or False

12 - Handcap True or False

13 - SMS_received 1 or more messages sent to the patient.

14 - No-show True or False.

Brief Summary of the Data Cleaning steps¶

The following changes were made to clean and transform the data

  • Duplicated data were dropped to ensure that the rows contains unique observations
  • Rows which were not necessary for the analysis were dropped
  • All column names were converted to the lowercase
  • No show column values is No for attended and yes for didnt attend and it was very confusing therefore I changed no-show column to showed to avoid confusion.
  • I changed the datatype of the appointmentdate and scheduleddate to datetime objects
  • Rows with values less than or equal to zero were droppped since someone's age can't be zero or less
  • I added some important features such as appointmentday week, month, etc to make analysis easy

Research Question: Does alcoholism affect patient's show up?¶

Let us define a function which we shall reuse to avoid repetitive code¶

In [25]:
def proportion_func(df,my_list,col_name):
    """
    This function calculates proportions for specific column by using pandas value_counts() and groupby()
    and returns the proportions if all input data are correct.
    It prints nice message to the user should bad input be supplied.
    
    Input: 
    - df : dataframe which contains all patients who showed up and didn't not show up for an appointment
    - my_list : This list contains column names that we need to groupby (groupby will be sorted the same way as my_list value sort)
    - col_name : column name (which we want to calculate proportion according to it)
    Output:
    - proportion : It's a pandas Series that contains grouped by my_list values and proportions according to col_name
    """
    try:
        if df.empty:
            raise Exception('dataframe is empty')
        for item in my_list: 
            if item not in df:
                raise Exception('one or more columns in my_list are not part of the dataframe')
        proportion = df.groupby(my_list)[col_name].value_counts(normalize=True).unstack(col_name)
        return proportion
    except Exception as error:
        print("You have entered bad input " + repr(error))

Now I'm going to use proportions_fun to calculate proportions for each factor trying to find correlations

Limitations¶

  • Appointmentday column has date without hours, minutes, and seconds which can be very important to studay against show rate.
  • No show column values is No for attended and yes for didnt attend and it was very confusing
  • The dataset does not contain sufficient data for the whole year - only three months are available for the appointmentday column.

Conclusions¶

  • The majority of people showed up for their scheduled appointment at about 79.9%
  • With respect to gender there is no differnece in the show up rate to appointment.
  • Alcoholism does not seem to affect patient show up rate
  • Diabetic patients tend to have slighly higher show up rate at approx. 82%
  • Receiving sms does not improve the patients appointment show up rate
  • About 32% received sms
